Description#1: Title from leader, "Bees nesting - Haselton." Photographer, Robert Neidrach. Close-up images of various bee species landing on flowers and burrowing into earth. Also includes views of men examining larvae in ground nests. Titles include "Bee: Nomia Bakeri," "Diodasia Australis, 'Bee of the Cactus,'" "Bee Anthophora Occidentalis, 'Bee of the Bank' (Fabre),"" and "Bee Melitoma Grisella, 'Bee of the Bush Morning Glory.'"

Description#1: Title on container: "Colorado birds I." Hand edited footage with descriptive intertitles, showing hikers and climbers around the Front Range, particularly as ascneding Longs Peak via the Cable route in Rocy Moutnain State Park, Colorado. Includes daytime and nighttime landscape views, men loading sleeping bags into a truck, a large camp site at meal time, deer, Ptarmigan, men showing off their torn trousers, women signing the "Colorado Mountain Club" register. Locations include Crater Lake, Fair Glacier, Longs Park, Timberline, Chasm Lake.
Description#2: Intertitles: 00:25 Rocks roll readily down the chimney, climbers go carefully, holding to rope; 01:28 Bob "Colorado" looks at the moraine of Fair Glacier, below is the ice-gouged valley; 01:50 Camp scenes at Crater Lake; 01:52 Flossie "Ohio" digs a hip hole to make sleeping more comfortable; 02:20 What rock climbing does to pants; 02:35 Longs Peak, highest in a land of lofty peaks; 02:5 Sleeping bags are loaded for two-night camp-out at timberline, 11,000 feet; 04:31 Ptarmigan, High Country Grouse, whose winter dress is pure white; 05:25 From Chasm View, Chasm Lake Louise, party of 34; 05:52 We rope over a snowbank and pull ourselves up by 150 feet of cable; 06:14 Doris "Iowa," Eppie "Texas," Catherine "Tennessee," and Lillian "New York" grasp the cable; 06:56 Bruce comes "over the top" on the end of cable; 07:12 Clara "Iowa" and Pat "Illinois" "make their marks" in the register; 07:25 Benchmark 174,255 feet, and Colorado Mountain Club register; 07:47 Julius wields an ice axe as we descend the homestretch; 08:40 Timberline trees for esthetes! Afternoon tea for tired feet!; 09:02 Elizabeth "Iowa" does a face-lifting job on Russ "Illinois"; 09:17 Early morning shots of deer and dears; 09:58 Gebhardt "Germany" and Chuck see how timberline tree grows in shelter of Boulder; 10:19 We hike in the rain from Chasm Lake.

Title#1: Snowy egerts of Avery Island Louisiana
Publisher#1: The Cockerell Film Library of the Palm Springs Desert Museum
Description#1: Title from container: "Conservation: The Snowy Egrets." Distributor, the Cockerell Film Library of the Palm Springs Desert Museum; photographer, Winfield Line. A history of the Snowy Egrets' near extinction and the founding of an Egret sanctuary by Edward McIllheny. Includes views of the santuary with visitors, the chinese Pagoda, lotus flowers, and other plants, with informational intertitles. The film notes that the population at this sanctuary had incresed from a very small population to more than 100,000 egrets. Also includes images of blue herons, anhingas (wild turkeys), insects, alligators, and other animals.

Description#1: Producer, Guy D. Haselton Travellettes; photographer, Guy D. Haselton. Images of California mission buildings with identifying intertitles
DescriptionLink#1: Intertitles: 00:00 Guy D. Haselton Travellettes presents Missions of California In The Footsteps Of The Padres Photographed by Guy D. Haselton Copyright MCMXXXIX All Rights Reserved 00:10 Civilization dawned in California July 16.1769 at San Diego with the founding of Mission San Diego de Alcala by Fray Junipero Serra, a Franciscan Friar. It was the first of 21 such outposts of Christianity extending 700 miles to the north. 00:36 With orders of the King of Spain to colonize the new land for Crown and Church, Serra made the terrible overland desert journey on foot. He was joined at San Diego by Don Gaspar de Portola, who came by sea. 01:03 Under the great Serra and Padre Fermin Lasuen, this successor, the Missions converted the Coast Indians, taught them useful trades. This Golden Age of California lasted 50 years. Today the vestiges of its glory form the state's most precious heritage. 01:34 San Diego de Alcala 1769 02:05 San Carlos de Carmel 1770 Burial place of Father Serra San Antonio de Padua 1771 03:19 San Gabriel Arcangel 1771 03:49 First grapevine in California. Planted by the Padres in 1775 at Mission 04:12 San Gabriel San Luis Obispo de Tolosa 1772 04:44 San Francisco de Assisi 1776 04:59 San Juan Capistrano 1776 05:53 Santa Clara de Assisi 1777 06:17 San Buenaventura 1782 06:57 Santa Barbara 1786 La Purisima Concepcion 1787 (before reconstruction) 8:10 La Purisima as it appears today 08:39 Site of Mission Santa Cruz 1791 08:50 La Soledad 1791 09:08 San Jose de Guadalupe 1797 09:22 San Juan Bautista 1797 10:08 San Miguel Arcangel 1797 10:47 San Fernando Rey de Espania 1797 San Luis Rey de Franca 1798 11:46 Planted in 1779 at Mission San Luis Rey, the first pepper tree in California still flourishes 12:31 Santa Ynez 1804 13:10 This pear tree is all that remains of Mission San Rafael Arcangel, founded in 1817 13:25 The last mission founded - San Francisco de Solano July 4, 1823 13:55 Gone is the pastoral simplicity of Mission days. Well more than a century has passed since the last building was dedicated at the end of El Camino Real. But the memory of a great accomplishment will long survive the crumbling walls that remain. 14:29 The End A Haselton Travelette

Publisher#1: United States Department of the Interior, National Parks Service
Description#1: Producer, United States Department of the Interior, National Parks Service. Images of plants, flowers, and animals native to Glacier National Park, with identifying intertitles. Species include snow bush, white lylac, sheep, antelope, porcupine, and beaver. Also includes images of "ranger naturalists" giving talks, tourists on horseback, and Blackfeet Indians performing dances.
DescriptionLink#1: Intertitles: 00:03 United States Department of the Interior National Park Service Presents 00:10 Natives of Glacier 00:22 Glacier National Park, in addition to its rugged mountain scenery, offers a notable variety of brilliant plants and flowers. 00:42 Ranger-naturalists give interesting talks on the many varieties; here's the showy Beardtongue. 01:04 The Snowbush, or White Lilac, adds its clustered beauty to the scene. 01:16 The White Dryad's attractive 8-petalled blossoms live but a short time. 01:29 Blue Lupine nestles against the sheltering rock. 01:41 Rock Cress, with its showy purple flowers, adds a colorful touch. 01:54 Wild Asters are readily identified by the daisy-like forms of their flower heads. 02:09 The Western Blue Flag, or Iris, with its background of fern-like Bracken, sways in the gentle breeze. 02:25 Indian Paint Bush - with its vivid coloring - is easily one of the showiest plants in the Park. 02:38 In the shaded, cool nooks, the shy Wood Nymph dots the mossy carpet. 02:50 False Solomon's Seal - at first glance - seems a cousin to our Lily of the Valley. 03:03 The low-lying, shrubby Dogwood with it's four-petalled, ivory-white blossoms, is common in Glacier National Park. 03:23 It is different from the tree-like flowering Dogwood of the east. 03:43 This floral blanket, hemmed in by graceful Alpine Firs, contains many unusual plants - 03:58 Fringed Parnassia, with its rare-colored feathered-edge blossoms. 04:16 - and in great abundance - Spotted Saxifrage, its small white flowers often dotted with yellow - 04:40 - also, Blue Phacelia, the blue of its blossoms reflecting the azure skies - 04:47 - the most attractive plant, Indian Bear or Basket Grass, deserves the closest attention. 05:12 Wild Life Abounds The Park horses plays a most important part in the sight-seeing. Once astride your "hand-picked" mount, both animal and bird habitats can be visited readily. 06:28 The ewes and lambs of Mountain Sheep often graze by themselves, though the rams are never far away. They scamper for safety at any sign of danger. 06:59 The Pronghorn, or American Antelope, once roamed this area. The National Park Service is endeavoring to restore them. 07:30 Rocky Mountain, or "Big Horn" sheep; the rams have massive, curling horns. The Marmot - or "Woodchuck" - enjoys doing nothing, and resents the interruption of his bath. 08:08 The Porcupine is one of the Park's most interesting inhabitants. 08:24 In the wooded valleys, both Grizzly and Black Bear are found. 08:44 Black Bears, excellent climbers, are at home off the ground. 09:03 Something arouses bruin's curiosity and he decides to investigate. 09:19 The Moose, largest of the antlered deer family, finds a haven in the Park's solitudes. 09:44 Small bands of Elk roam the meadows; they browse and graze --- unmolested. 10:09 Canada Geese - noted migratory travelers and largest of our wild game birds, also nest in the Park. 10:31 The Beaver, once facing extinction, now thrives under the areas protected by the National Park Service. 10:51 The Marten - three pounds of furry animation, in inquisitive and predatory. 11:06 The gaily-striped Chipmunks are friendly little bundles of furry activity. 11:24 The Golden-Mantled ground squirrel is always active, friendly -- and hungry. 11:42 The Blue-fronted Jay is the campers' liveliest entertainer. 11:56 Fond of nuts, the Golden-Mantled ground squirrel chases the poaching Clark's Nutcracker. 12:19 Blackfeet Indians, from their reservation bordering the Park, welcome an occasional visit - 12:48 - and entertain their visitors by performing some of their tribal dances and ceremonies. 13:40 The End Department of the Interior National Park Service Production

Description#1: Close-up images of hummingbirds, with informational intertitles.
DescriptionLink#1: Intertitles: 00:00 The nest of the Humming Bird, called Eurynome Hermit, is so small that it resembles a tangled, wind tossed spider's web. 00:14 In reality, it is fashioned from cobwebs purloined from the home of the Spider, woven together with vegetable fibres and lined with the softest, downy substance. 00:37 There are no more interesting birds or a species with more entrancing charm than are the Humming Birds. Their brilliance is unequaled and only to be described by comparison to precious stones. 01:01 The little mother is very solicitous and feeds the young hermits with honey collected from the flowers. 01:16 To see these helpless babes rocked by the breeze it is hard to realize that they will soon become such beautifully formed and colored birds of such wonderful speed and action. 01:46 The region of the Amazon basin, richest in flowers and color is the "Ceja" or bush country that fringes the tree limits, the home of the Humming Birds. 02:17 The species known as Ruby and Topaz builds its nest in the fork of a Bayberry bush. The tiniest cradle in the world lined with Dandelion silk. 02:40 The nest is never left alone, but for a few moments, after the eggs are laid. Either the male or female is on the nest until the young appear. 03:22 The slumbers of the tiniest babes of all bird life are often disturbed by foraging ants, nearly as large as the fledglings. 03:53 The nests of the Humming Birds, like the birds themselves, vary with distinct individual characteristics, but the solicitation for the young and care of the home is the same in all species.

Description#2: Intertitles: 00:45 This sulphur mining process was invented in 1891 by Dr. Herman Frasch, a noted chemist. It was brought to successful operation in 1903. Description#1: Hand edited film of the University of Colorado Boulder campus and students in a mountaineering club. Includes shots of Norlin Library, Sewell Hall, Varsity Lake, the McKenna Building, the Law Building and other university buildings, in summer, fall, and winter (1939-1941). Mountain club footage includes sleeping bags drying on the lawn of the Law School, a "steak and trout fry" picnic near the foothills, Chautauqua Park, the Flatirons, a nighttime "Honorary Degree" ceremony and bonfire, Tom Hutchinson, students rappelling for "masters degrees," and students hiking in the snow. Also includes views of Flagstaff Mountain, Arapahoe Glacier, and Blue Lake.
Description#2: Intertitles: 00::36 This is the way we water the lawn; 02:07 Sleeping bags and blankets are sunned before Law Building; 02:16 From 7,000-foot Flagstaff Mountain--The Front Range; 02:37 Arapaho Glacier and Peaks, 13,000 feet above the sea; 02:48 Steak & trout frys tuesdays and thursdays in the Foothills; 03:18 "Chuck" leads singing, talks up high country; 03:37 From Flagstaff we look down to Mile-High campus; 03:48 Tom Hutchinson, Doctor of Mountaineering, makes cocoa; 04:21 Graham Bolton, Isabelle Daniels rappel for Master's Degrees; 04:57 Honorary degrees are conferred, July 14th; 05:27 "Perched erratics" below the peak, above the valley; 05:32 "Sitting resters," hobnailed legs at ice-covered Blue Lake, June 20; 06:00 Lunch time on 12,900-foot peak; 06:11 With wet "aftermaths" to dry at campfire
Description#3: Title on case: Mountain Climbing in the Front Range 1938

Description#1: Filmmakers Ed and Jean Hoff. Footage of broadtail hummingbirds in a mountain landscape setting. Includes informational intertitles on male and female characteristics, nesting, and raising young. Shows humans interacting with adult birds, as well as newly born chicks. Chosen by Movie Makers Magazine (Amateur Cinema League, Inc.) as one of the ten best non-theatrical films of 1940.
Description#2: Intertitles: 00:08 Foreword: The Broadtail Hummingbird is no larger than one's thumb and weighs less than a penny. Yet his courage and lightning attack has caused the lordly eagle to veer from his flight; 00:20 No bird on earth can match the dashing flight, flashing plumage and gallant wooing of this gorgeous sprite of the airways; 00:30 In the scenes which follow, many of them never before photographed, you will see the full life cycle of the Broadtailed Hummer. He is common throughout the west and deceptively similar to the eastern Ruby-throat; 00:38 Finding a nest; 00:59 The male: A restless, carefree fellow who takes no part in the nest building, incubation or rearing of the young. His throat, typical of most male hummers, changes from soft black to flashing red; 01:32 Note the needle-like tongue; 02:14 The female: Iridescent throat speckles vary from practically none to a conspicuous spot; 03:04 Building the nest: The nest, about the size of a walnut, is built of cotton-like material stuccoed with flakes of bark. Spider webs are used to bind the materials together and anchor the nest to the twig; 03:54 Each nest contains two eggs about the size of many beans. Incubation requires about 15 days; 05:16 Five days old: The young are fed a mixture of partly digested insects and nectar; 06:04 The body is full grown at 15 days; 07:00 Twenty days old: At 20 days the nest is battered down by their active preparation for flight. The cautious young Hummers never fall as they leave the nest; 08:27 they can fly at 20 days but usually 5 days more are spent on the nest, fanning and testing their wings to assure a successful first flight; 08:54 Number 1 takes off.
